Hello Yash Jain,

Greetings from PharmEasy!

We refer to your below mail & Order id ​6231414
​Based on your complaint, please be assured that corrective measures will be taken in line with our company policy to ensure such lapses are avoided in the future.

We would like to inform you that the hematoma around the vein puncture site after blood collection is usually harmless and it will heal naturally.
Though there could be pain, Here's what you can do to speed up the healing process:
 
•    Apply ice packs to the affected area 2-3 times a day, for about 15 minutes, for the first two days.
•    You may begin intermittent heat therapy (also 15 minutes) in addition to the ice, either by soaking the arm, by hot water bottle, or with a heating pad.
 
In case you develop severe symptoms such as intense pain, discoloration or major swelling, kindly consult with your doctor immediately.

We understand your concerns & sincerely regret the inconvenience caused to you.

For any further assistance, please reopen this ticket or reach out to us through our support channels, in the App or website, listed in the 'Need Help' section.
Thank you for choosing PharmEasy. Have a great day ahead!

Hello Pharmeasy Team,

I refer to my order number 651467699255189504 dated 23rd November 2025 where one of the medicines ordered was 6 strips of Urotone DS. Instead of sending Urotone DS, Pharmeasy delivered Urotone 25 mg. I called Pharmeasy on 29th November and spoke to Vijay who arranged for a pick-up of the wrong medicine, and he assured me that if I place the order again the correct medicine would be sent.

Hence, I placed another order number 653660461726171136 dated 29th November 2025 which included 6 strips of Urotone DS. Once again Pharmeasy delivered Urotone 25 mg instead of Urotone DS. On 30th November I called Pharmeasy and spoke to Lata who assured me that matter would be investigated and that I would receive a call from the warehouse explaining the issue.

I also received one SMS on 30th November stating that my concern # 22239256 has been escalated and that Pharmeasy was committed to resolving it within 24 to 48 hours.

A further SMS was received on 2nd December apologizing for the delay in resolving the concern and that the Pharmeasy team was actively working on it.

It has been over a week since the last SMS and Pharmeasy has not provided a response as to why the same wrong medicine was sent twice.

I trust that you understand the gravity of sending wrong dosage of medicines twice and it speaks volumes of the lack of controls at your warehouse.

Mr. Himanshu,

Please investigate the issue and revert with an explanation for these serious lapses as the warehouse team has not got in touch with me.

Yours Sincerely,

Zarine B. Mulla.
